the introduction of the Swiss Bond Index (SBI) and the Swiss Bond Index-Euro (SBI-Euro).

Both the SBI as well as the SBI-Euro are defined as result of a new way of measuring asset return and to control risk over time and over different bonds. These indices are used by investment professionals to mirror the performance of the bond market and also the exposure of that particular bond against interest rate risk.

Essentially, a bond index of an average Swiss bond product of the largest Swiss issuer with the highest average rating is defined. It measures the aggregate exposure of a bond in international and domestic bond markets.

The SBI is meant to measure overall bond performance for Swiss lock-unlock schemes, and the SBI-Euro is meant to summarise the performance of foreign bonds that are denominated in Swiss francs. It is a good advocate for investors using this as information for investment management purposes.

Despite these indices being new to the market, there are still a few criteria that need to be met before bonds can be included in these indices. DBMAS has just recently met these criteria that will give us access to the risk that the indices seek to mirror. HYROs are easily adaptable to meet SBI components.
